message: To get a high score, consistently follow these steps: 1. Use the 'stove' on a raw protein (e.g., raw egg, raw bacon, raw beef) to cook it. This item will be worth 20. 2. message: Focus on cooking raw proteins with the stove first; they consistently gain 20 value. Cook grains and some vegetables with the stove as well, even if their individual value doesn't immediately increase, as this is crucial for combining. Combining cooked protein + cooked grain often yields 40 value. Adding a second cooked protein or a cooked vegetable (that itself has value like cooked potato) to this combo can reach 60 or 80. Avoid combining too many different raw or simply 'cooked' vegetable/grain items into an already complex dish, as this can dramatically reduce value or make it negative. The water tool seemed to have no positive impact on value in my attempts. Aim for 2-3 cooked, complementary components for high scores. Good luck!

message: The 'stove' tool is your best friend! Use it on raw proteins (bacon, egg, beef) and most vegetables (potato, carrot, cucumber) to get value 20 'cooked' ingredients. Use it on grains (bread, corn, wheat) to get 'cooked' grains, though they remain value 0 initially. Combine a 'cooked protein' with a 'cooked vegetable' for value 60. Then, add a 'cooked grain' to that combination to reach value 80. Avoid adding 'raw' or 'soaked' items, especially vegetables, to complex cooked dishes as it can severely drop the value to negative. The 'water' tool didn't seem to add value in my rounds.
